  "response_text": "This is a comprehensive, science-backed muscle-building plan designed for a beginner to intermediate lifter. It focuses on **progressive overload** (gradually increasing weight/reps), **compound movements**, and **proper recovery**.\n\n### The Core Principles\n1.  **Train 3-4 days per week.** More is not better; recovery is where muscle grows.\n2.  **Lift heavy (for you).** You should struggle to complete the last 1-2 reps of each set.\n3.  **Eat in a slight calorie surplus.** You need extra energy to build tissue.\n4.  **Eat enough protein.** Aim for **1.6g to 2.2g of protein per kg of body weight** (e.g., a 80kg person needs 128g-176g of protein daily).\n\n---\n\n## The Plan: Full Body (3 Days/Week)\n\nThis is the most effective schedule for beginners. It hits every major muscle group 3 times a week.\n\n**Day A (Monday) - Strength Focus**\n| Exercise | Sets | Reps | Rest |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Barbell Back Squat | 4 | 5-8 | 90-120 sec |\n| Barbell Bench Press | 4 | 6-10 | 90 sec |\n| Bent-Over Barbell Row | 4 | 6-10 | 90 sec |\n| Dumbbell Shoulder Press | 3 | 8-12 | 60 sec |\n| Leg Press (or Lunges) | 3 | 10-15 | 60 sec |\n| Plank | 3 | 45-60 sec | 45 sec |\n\n**Day B (Wednesday) - Hypertrophy Focus**\n| Exercise | Sets | Reps | Rest |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Deadlift (Conventional or Romanian) | 4 | 5-8 | 120 sec |\n| Incline Dumbbell Press | 4 | 8-12 | 60-90 sec |\n| Pull-Ups (or Lat Pulldown) | 4 | As many reps as possible (AMRAP) | 90 sec |\n| Dumbbell Lateral Raises | 3 | 12-15 | 45 sec |\n| Barbell Curl (Biceps) | 3 | 8-12 | 60 sec |\n| Triceps Pushdown (or Dips) | 3 | 8-12 | 60 sec |\n\n**Day C (Friday) - Volume & Accessories**\n| Exercise | Sets | Reps | Rest |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Goblet Squat (or Front Squat) | 3 | 10-15 | 60 sec |\n| Dumbbell Row (One-Arm) | 4 | 8-12 each side | 60 sec |\n| Flat Dumbbell Press | 4 | 8-12 | 60 sec |\n| Face Pull (Rear Delt & Posture) | 3 | 15-20 | 45 sec |\n| Leg Curl (Hamstrings) | 3 | 10-15 | 60 sec |\n| Calf Raises | 4 | 15-20 | 45 sec |\n| Hanging Leg Raises (Abs) | 3 | 10-15 | 45 sec |\n\n---\n\n## How to Progress (The Most Important Part)\n\nYou must increase the challenge over time. Use the **Double Progression** method:\n- **Rep Goal:** Aim for the top of the rep range (e.g., 8 reps for a 6-8 set).\n- **Add Weight:** Once you can hit the top rep for **all sets**, increase the weight by the smallest increment (e.g., 2.5kg/5lbs) on your next workout.\n- **Drop Reps:** You will likely only get 5-6 reps with the new weight. That's fine. Build back up to 8 reps.\n- **Repeat.** This is the engine of muscle growth.\n\n---\n\n## Nutrition & Recovery\n\n### Daily Targets (Example for an 80kg person)\n- **Calories:** 2,600 - 2,800 (Maintenance + ~300 surplus)\n- **Protein:** 140g - 180g (Chicken, eggs, whey, tofu, Greek yogurt)\n- **Carbs:** 300g - 350g (Rice, oats, potatoes, fruit)\n- **Fats:** 60g - 80g (Olive oil, nuts, avocado)\n\n### Sample Meal Structure (for 150g protein)\n- **Breakfast:** 3 eggs + 2 slices whole wheat toast + 1 cup Greek yogurt.\n- **Lunch:** 200g chicken breast + 1 cup rice + broccoli.\n- **Dinner:** 200g lean beef/ salmon + sweet potato + green beans.\n- **Snack:** 1 scoop whey protein + banana + handful of almonds.\n\n### Recovery Non-Negotiables\n- **Sleep:** 7-9 hours per night. This is when testosterone and growth hormone peak.\n- **Hydration:** 3-4 liters of water daily.\n- **Deload Week:** Every 6-8 weeks, do one week with 50% of your normal weight. This prevents burnout and injury.\n\n---\n\n## Common Mistakes to Avoid\n1.  **Ego Lifting:** Sacrificing form for weight. You will get injured. Use a weight you can control.\n2.  **Skipping Legs:** Squats and deadlifts release the most muscle-building hormones (testosterone, GH). Don't skip them.\n3.  **Not Tracking:** Write down your lifts. If you don't know what you did last week, you can't progress.\n4.  **Too Much Cardio:** 2-3 sessions of 20-30 min LISS (walking, incline treadmill) is fine. Avoid marathon running while bulking.\n\n**Final Advice:** Stick with this plan for **12 weeks**. Do not change exercises every week. The boring, consistent work is what builds muscle. Take progress photos every 4 weeks to see changes the mirror might miss.",
